00:55:56.260 --> 00:55:59.190
So we'll use it, but
it's not something

00:55:59.190 --> 00:56:01.860
that directly-- it's an outcome
of putting things together,

00:56:01.860 --> 00:56:05.070
not so much something
that we built in.

00:56:05.070 --> 00:56:12.050
If we talk about heavy quark
and light quark symmetries,

00:56:12.050 --> 00:56:23.657
so SQ cross Sl, then
it's 1/2, 1/2 under that.

00:56:23.657 --> 00:56:25.990
So if we work in the rest
frame, which is this vr, which

00:56:25.990 --> 00:56:32.570
is 1, 0, then you have--

00:56:32.570 --> 00:56:35.750
if you think about doing
a symmetry transformation,

00:56:35.750 --> 00:56:38.140
you get a commutator,
and basically

00:56:38.140 --> 00:56:42.340
what happens is
that you would get--

00:56:42.340 --> 00:56:45.260
you have two sets of--
you have a bispinor,

00:56:45.260 --> 00:56:47.350
so you have two parts
of the spinor that

00:56:47.350 --> 00:56:49.180
are corresponding to the
heavy quark and two parts that

00:56:49.180 --> 00:56:50.722
are corresponding
to the light quark.

00:56:50.722 --> 00:56:56.830
The heavy quark
part is on the left,

00:56:56.830 --> 00:57:01.120
and then the light quark
part is on the right.

00:57:13.430 --> 00:57:15.170
That's the spin transformations.

00:57:15.170 --> 00:57:17.720
And this is the right spin
transformation for something

00:57:17.720 --> 00:57:21.605
that's spin 1/2,
where the sigma 4 by 4

00:57:21.605 --> 00:57:22.985
is the usual spin matrix.

00:57:37.790 --> 00:57:40.280
Let me just say a bit more
about heavy quark spin

00:57:40.280 --> 00:57:48.130
symmetry, which is part
of our discussion there.

00:57:48.130 --> 00:57:49.870
So Hv is transforming.

00:57:49.870 --> 00:57:53.210
If you do a heavy quark spin
symmetry transformation,

00:57:53.210 --> 00:57:54.460
it's transforming on the left.

00:57:54.460 --> 00:57:58.510
That's what I just
was discussing.

00:57:58.510 --> 00:58:02.110
And if you do some
transformation parameterized

00:58:02.110 --> 00:58:06.100
by some theta, which I just
dot into the S over there,

00:58:06.100 --> 00:58:09.340
then this is the way
we think about what

00:58:09.340 --> 00:58:11.620
the transformation gives.

00:58:11.620 --> 00:58:15.730
So you could take this, and
you could plug in our Hv field

00:58:15.730 --> 00:58:18.610
and then just do
the Dirac algebra

00:58:18.610 --> 00:58:22.450
with the gamma and the gamma
5 and simplify this thing down

00:58:22.450 --> 00:58:31.195
and work out a transformation
for delta pv and delta pv star.

00:58:34.950 --> 00:58:43.050
And what you'd find is that this
guy in the rest frame here--

00:58:43.050 --> 00:58:53.290
everything in the rest frame is
that, and this guy, theta cross

00:58:53.290 --> 00:59:01.423
pvr star minus 1/2 theta pvr.

00:59:01.423 --> 00:59:03.090
So if you talk about
the transformations

00:59:03.090 --> 00:59:06.330
under heavy quark spin
symmetry of the states,

00:59:06.330 --> 00:59:09.007
these are actually getting
mixed up into each other.

00:59:09.007 --> 00:59:10.590
And that's what we
already were saying

00:59:10.590 --> 00:59:12.548
before when we were
talking about spectroscopy,

00:59:12.548 --> 00:59:14.850
that spin symmetry
was relating the two.

00:59:14.850 --> 00:59:17.760
This is us now seeing
that very explicitly,

00:59:17.760 --> 00:59:20.270
that if you make a heavy quark
spin symmetry transformation,

00:59:20.270 --> 00:59:22.410
the vector guy--

00:59:22.410 --> 00:59:25.290
so this guy should have a star--

00:59:25.290 --> 00:59:28.740
and the scalar guy get mixed up.

00:59:28.740 --> 00:59:30.960
And that's what spin
symmetry allows you to do,

00:59:30.960 --> 00:59:33.660
is relate any
statements about the v

00:59:33.660 --> 00:59:35.340
to statements about the v star.

00:59:35.340 --> 00:59:37.950
It's one thing it
allows you to do.

00:59:37.950 --> 00:59:42.180
So the power of
this Hvr thing is

00:59:42.180 --> 00:59:47.940
that it allows us to make
heavy quark spin symmetry

00:59:47.940 --> 00:59:53.820
predictions easily
because we've encoded

00:59:53.820 --> 00:59:55.080
the symmetry in this object.

00:59:55.080 --> 00:59:57.420
Kind of like our
spurion analysis,

00:59:57.420 --> 01:00:01.020
we'll be able to use
similar types of ideas

01:00:01.020 --> 01:00:04.747
to make spin symmetry
predictions easy with this guy.

01:00:04.747 --> 01:00:06.330
So let me give you
an example of that.

01:00:10.900 --> 01:00:16.050
So an example is talking about
heavy quark decay constants.

01:00:16.050 --> 01:00:18.430
And we can think about
B mesons or D mesons.

01:00:21.330 --> 01:00:23.220
Correspondingly, B
stars and D stars.

01:00:30.960 --> 01:00:34.170
So think of the Q field here
that I'm writing as a full QCD

01:00:34.170 --> 01:00:37.980
field, and the p field
here with momentum p,

01:00:37.980 --> 01:00:40.350
it's either a B
meson or a D meson.

01:00:43.020 --> 01:00:46.020
And just by Lorentz
symmetry, much like one

01:00:46.020 --> 01:00:48.570
works out for the pion,
one can write down

01:00:48.570 --> 01:00:53.443
a result that just falls from
Lorentz invariance and parity

01:00:53.443 --> 01:00:55.110
for what the result
for this coefficient

01:00:55.110 --> 01:00:57.075
is, because you also have
to use time reversal.

01:01:05.400 --> 01:01:07.410
And you could also
write the p as mp times

01:01:07.410 --> 01:01:10.500
v if you want to make
explicit that there's

01:01:10.500 --> 01:01:13.860
some velocity that this
thing, that this p squares

01:01:13.860 --> 01:01:17.080
to the mass of that state.

01:01:17.080 --> 01:01:20.860
So this guy here is some
dimension 1 constant.

01:01:20.860 --> 01:01:27.750
And if we just, in
QCD, do the same thing

01:01:27.750 --> 01:01:34.320
for the other guy,
which is the vector,

01:01:34.320 --> 01:01:36.720
we can do the same game.

01:01:36.720 --> 01:01:38.430
Here we have to
get a polarization

01:01:38.430 --> 01:01:39.818
on the right-hand side.

01:01:39.818 --> 01:01:41.610
There has to be linear
in the polarization.

01:01:41.610 --> 01:01:43.830
That's the statement
about a vector.

01:01:43.830 --> 01:01:46.980
And because of parity, it's
not the gamma mu, gamma phi,

01:01:46.980 --> 01:01:49.590
but the gamma mu that
comes in because we

01:01:49.590 --> 01:01:52.330
have spin 1 instead of spin 0.

01:01:52.330 --> 01:01:54.160
So there's an extra
minus 1 from that.

01:01:54.160 --> 01:01:56.070
So instead of-- so we
have a gamma mu here,

01:01:56.070 --> 01:01:58.110
and this is how we can
parameterize the matrix

01:01:58.110 --> 01:01:58.950
element.

01:01:58.950 --> 01:02:01.290
And this guy here, if we
work out the dimensions,

01:02:01.290 --> 01:02:03.090
it would be dimension 2.

01:02:03.090 --> 01:02:05.070
So just in QCD, it
looks like we have

01:02:05.070 --> 01:02:08.400
these two things, fp and fp
star, that are different.

01:02:08.400 --> 01:02:12.180
But we know heavy quark symmetry
relates the p and the p star,

01:02:12.180 --> 01:02:14.230
so they actually
should be related.

01:02:14.230 --> 01:02:16.650
So you could ask the question,
how are they related?

01:02:16.650 --> 01:02:18.032
Work it out.

01:02:18.032 --> 01:02:19.740
And if I asked you
that question, the way

01:02:19.740 --> 01:02:22.710
to work it out, which I'll show
you, is to use this Hv field.

01:02:25.890 --> 01:02:28.560
OK, so there's two things
we have to work out.

01:02:28.560 --> 01:02:31.420
We have to-- we're going
to use the Hv field.

01:02:31.420 --> 01:02:32.170
I'll show you how.

01:02:32.170 --> 01:02:33.930
We also have to think
about these currents

01:02:33.930 --> 01:02:36.780
that I've talked about here and
writing them in terms of the Qv

01:02:36.780 --> 01:02:39.090
field, so let's do that first.

01:02:51.000 --> 01:02:53.280
So that's pretty easy.

01:02:58.650 --> 01:03:01.200
Just replace our
field by the Qv field.

01:03:22.555 --> 01:03:24.930
Now, if I just want to make
a statement about heavy quark

01:03:24.930 --> 01:03:27.570
symmetry, then I can look
at how this guy transforms

01:03:27.570 --> 01:03:29.070
under heavy quark
symmetry because I

01:03:29.070 --> 01:03:31.350
know how Qv transforms
under heavy quark symmetry.

01:03:38.190 --> 01:03:46.800
So [INAUDIBLE] D.

01:03:46.800 --> 01:03:49.200
And so what I'd like
to do is I'd like

01:03:49.200 --> 01:03:52.410
to encode in a general object--

01:03:55.925 --> 01:03:57.800
much as we did in chiral
perturbation theory,

01:03:57.800 --> 01:04:03.860
I'd like to encode in a general
object that involves the Hv

01:04:03.860 --> 01:04:07.940
field something that has
the same transformation

01:04:07.940 --> 01:04:10.280
properties as this current.

01:04:25.900 --> 01:04:28.540
Much in the same way we
could think about putting--

01:04:28.540 --> 01:04:30.760
connecting currents that
transformed in a certain way

01:04:30.760 --> 01:04:32.260
to a chiral theory, we're
doing the same thing

01:04:32.260 --> 01:04:33.070
with heavy quarks.

01:04:36.570 --> 01:04:40.710
So let's pretend--
in order to do this,

01:04:40.710 --> 01:04:43.110
instead of thinking
about covariance,

01:04:43.110 --> 01:04:44.610
