01:06:50.690 --> 01:06:52.360
So there's two things
that we can do.

01:06:52.360 --> 01:06:55.455
We can write down something
that just is a diagonal

01:06:55.455 --> 01:06:56.705
or something that's a v slash.

01:06:59.470 --> 01:07:01.300
But then we can
simplify this guy

01:07:01.300 --> 01:07:06.020
because Hv v slash is minus Hv.

01:07:06.020 --> 01:07:08.000
See, I can take this,
and this is a trace,

01:07:08.000 --> 01:07:09.790
so I can move it over to
the other side of the trace,

01:07:09.790 --> 01:07:11.998
and if it's a v slash on
the other side of the trace,

01:07:11.998 --> 01:07:13.850
then I can use this formula.

01:07:13.850 --> 01:07:17.380
And so these two guys
here actually just become,

01:07:17.380 --> 01:07:21.700
after taking that into account,
one thing, which I'll just call

01:07:21.700 --> 01:07:23.390
a.

01:07:23.390 --> 01:07:24.850
So there's basically
a unique thing

01:07:24.850 --> 01:07:26.230
that we can write
down for the x.

01:07:26.230 --> 01:07:29.680
After we use all the symmetry
properties of the Hv,

01:07:29.680 --> 01:07:31.970
we only have one thing.

01:07:31.970 --> 01:07:34.930
And so then you can just
work out what that trace is.

01:07:38.830 --> 01:07:40.480
Just take the trace.

01:07:40.480 --> 01:07:46.990
And you get a, and you
get minus i v mu pv,

01:07:46.990 --> 01:07:52.930
or you get pv star mu,
and this is what you get

01:07:52.930 --> 01:07:55.163
if you have gamma mu, gamma 5.

01:07:55.163 --> 01:07:57.080
And this is what you get
if you have gamma mu,

01:07:57.080 --> 01:07:58.960
and if you have the other way--

01:07:58.960 --> 01:08:01.210
so for gamma mu, you don't
get any pseudoscalar,

01:08:01.210 --> 01:08:03.430
and for gamma mu gamma 5,
